  <p style="font-weight: 600; font-size: 1.1em; margin-bottom: 1.5em; color: #d32f2f;">
    <strong>Direct answer:</strong> Yes, cannabis scams are extremely common in Madrid. Tourist scammers operate in Sol, Gran Vía, Malasaña, and every major hostel.
  </p>

  <section id="overview">
    <h2>Why Madrid Cannabis Scams Are So Common</h2>

    <p>Madrid is the #1 cannabis scam destination in Spain. Why? Because 8+ million tourists visit annually, most of them under 35, looking to try cannabis in a city where the legal status is confusing and the club system is opaque.</p>

    <p>Scammers know three things work:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Language barriers:</strong> Tourists can't easily verify legitimacy or read fine print</li>
      <li><strong>One-time customers:</strong> You'll never come back to complain or take legal action</li>
      <li><strong>Police risk perception:</strong> Tourists are afraid to report scams because they were breaking the law</li>
    </ul>

    <p>We've spoken to tourists who lost €50-200 to fake delivery services, street dealers selling oregano, and "clubs" that disappeared after taking a membership fee. Some ended up hospitalized from synthetic cannabinoids sold as THC-heavy flower.</p>

    <div class="alert alert--danger">
      <strong>⚠️ The Reality:</strong> What gets sold on the streets of Puerta del Sol, Gran Vía, Calle Montera, and outside hostels is often oregano, CBD hemp with zero THC, or synthetic cannabinoids that can trigger seizures, rapid heart rate, and severe paranoia. It is not cannabis. It is a criminal product designed to separate you from your money.
    </div>
  </section>

  <section id="street-dealers">
    <h2>Scam #1: Street Dealers ("The Handshake")</h2>

    <p><strong>Where it happens:</strong> Puerta del Sol, Gran Vía, Calle Montera, Plaza de Chueca, outside major hostels, train stations</p>

    <p>The street dealer scam is the oldest and most aggressive. A man approaches you (usually between 20-45, often North African or Eastern European) and offers to sell you cannabis, hash, or "the best weed in Madrid."</p>

    <h3>The "Handshake" Tactic</h3>

    <p>Here's exactly how it works—we've documented this from dozens of tourist accounts:</p>

    <ol>
      <li><strong>The approach:</strong> "You look for smoke? I have the best product, my friend. Very good quality."</li>
      <li><strong>The negotiation:</strong> They quote a price (usually €50-80 for "1 gram," €100+ for "5 grams"). You agree verbally.</li>
      <li><strong>The handshake:</strong> They extend their hand for a handshake. As you shake, they force a tiny bag (containing dried oregano, hemp shake, or synthetic powder) into your palm and close your fingers around it.</li>
      <li><strong>The demand:</strong> "Give me the money NOW." Their associates stand nearby, making clear this isn't a friendly negotiation.</li>
      <li><strong>The reality:</strong> You hand over €50-100 for something that is not cannabis.</li>
    </ol>

    <p>The psychological trick is that you now "own" the product (even though you don't want it), so the social pressure to pay is immense. If you refuse, you're confronted by 2-3 associates, and the situation escalates.</p>

    <h3>What They're Actually Selling</h3>

    <p><strong>Laboratory analysis of seized street products in Madrid (2024-2025) shows:</strong></p>
    <ul>
      <li>60% oregano, dried rosemary, or garden herbs</li>
      <li>20% CBD hemp flower (legal, but 0% THC—you won't feel anything)</li>
      <li>15% synthetic cannabinoids (MDMB-4en-PINACA, ADB-BUTINACA, or similar)</li>
      <li>5% actual cannabis (extremely rare)</li>
    </ul>

    <p>The synthetic cannabinoids are the dangerous ones. They're 5-10x more potent than THC, not tested for safety, and have sent tourists to Hospital Clínico and Gregorio Marañón with tachycardia, seizures, and acute psychosis.</p>

    <h3>The "Free Sample" Play</h3>

    <p>Some dealers offer a "free sample" of a few pieces to build trust. The sample is real (or close to it), so you think the full bag will be too. When you buy the full amount, it's 80% filler.</p>

    <h3>Police Activity</h3>

    <p>Police regularly patrol Sol, Gran Vía, and Malasaña. If you're caught with a bag—even one you just bought—you can face a €601-€30,000 administrative fine for public possession. You cannot say "I was scammed" to reduce this; the fine is issued regardless.</p>

    <div class="alert alert--warning">
      <strong>If approached by a street dealer:</strong> Do not accept a handshake. Do not touch any product. Clearly say "No, thank you" and walk away. If they follow you, go into a restaurant, bar, or police station. Street dealers work on foot and avoid police, so entering a crowded public space breaks their power.
    </div>
  </section>

  <section id="fake-clubs">
    <h2>Scam #2: Fake Cannabis Clubs</h2>

    <p><strong>Where it happens:</strong> Gran Vía, Malasaña, Chueca, Sol—anywhere with high foot traffic</p>

    <p>Fake "cannabis clubs" are the most sophisticated scam. They look and feel real but are designed to take your membership fee (€20-50) and never let you actually buy anything, or sell you low-quality product at inflated prices.</p>

    <h3>The Fake Club Tactic</h3>

    <p>A well-dressed man (often with a printed flyer or clipboard) approaches you on Gran Vía or near a metro station:</p>

    <p><em>"Hi, I work for a cannabis social club nearby. We're very exclusive, very safe. Very Spanish law. You need a friend who is already a member to get in—but I can sponsor you right now. Just €30 membership fee and you can shop inside, no problem."</em></p>

    <p>What actually happens:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>You're taken to a room that looks like a cannabis club (a small office with some plants, maybe a menu on the wall)</li>
      <li>They take your €30 and ask for your ID</li>
      <li>They print a fake membership card (takes 2 minutes, 0 legitimacy)</li>
      <li>You're told the "shop" is closed today, but you can come back tomorrow</li>
      <li>When you return (if you do), no one recognizes the card, or it's "not in the system"</li>
    </ul>

    <p>Alternatively, they sell you product directly from a small stash, but the quality is extremely poor and the price is 3-4x what you'd pay at a real club (€40 for an eighth-ounce instead of €10-15).</p>

    <h3>How to Spot a Fake Club on the Street</h3>

    <ul>
      <li><strong>They approach you:</strong> Real clubs never recruit on the street. Never. They're registered as non-profit associations; they don't need foot traffic.</li>
      <li><strong>They offer instant membership:</strong> Real clubs require a verified member to invite you, an interview, and proof of residency. It takes days or weeks.</li>
      <li><strong>They take cash immediately:</strong> Real clubs issue a membership card after you sign legal paperwork and provide ID.</li>
      <li><strong>The location is sketchy:</strong> Real clubs have fixed, legal addresses. If they're meeting you in an alley or taking you to a hidden door, it's fake.</li>
      <li><strong>No menu or pricing:</strong> Real clubs have transparent menus with prices. If you ask "how much?" and they say "depends, what do you want?"—fake.</li>
    </ul>

