  <section id="delivery-scams">
    <h2>Scam #3: WhatsApp & Telegram Delivery Scams</h2>

    <p><strong>Where it happens:</strong> Online, via stickers on lampposts near hostels, in WhatsApp groups for tourists</p>

    <p>Cannabis delivery is illegal in Spain. There is no legal delivery service. Anyone offering it—via sticker, WhatsApp, Telegram, or any other channel—is running a scam. Period.</p>

    <h3>How the Scam Works</h3>

    <p>You see a sticker on a lamppost near your hostel with a Telegram or WhatsApp handle. Or someone in a hostel group chat offers "fast delivery to your room, 20 mins, €50/gram." You message them.</p>

    <p><strong>What happens next:</strong></p>

    <ol>
      <li><strong>They ask for advance payment:</strong> "Send €50 via Wise, PayPal, or bank transfer first. We deliver after payment."</li>
      <li><strong>You send money:</strong> You Wise €50 to their account (they have a Spanish or EU bank account, often registered under a fake name).</li>
      <li><strong>They disappear:</strong> No delivery. Number blocked. Your €50 is gone.</li>
      <li><strong>Or, they "deliver":</strong> A bag arrives via a courier (Glovo, Uber Eats, or personal drop-off). Inside: oregano or synthetic product, not cannabis.</li>
    </ol>

    <p>Some scammers run the long con: they deliver a small amount of real or decent product on the first order (€30-50), building trust. On the second order, you send €150+ for a large amount. Nothing arrives. The account is abandoned, and you've lost significant money.</p>

    <h3>The Lamppost Sticker Network</h3>

    <p>Stickers appear near every major hostel: Puerta del Sol, Malasaña, Chueca. They're professional-looking, often with QR codes and "24/7 DELIVERY" in English. The network is run by organized scam rings, not individuals. Each sticker generates dozens of attempts per day; even a 10% conversion rate (people who actually send money) is profitable.</p>

    <h3>Why This Scam Works So Well</h3>

    <ul>
      <li><strong>Convenience:</strong> You don't have to leave your hostel or risk talking to street dealers</li>
      <li><strong>Anonymous:</strong> No face-to-face interaction, so scammers feel safe</li>
      <li><strong>Plausible deniability:</strong> Scammers operate from different countries; Wise doesn't verify identity for small transfers; they're gone before authorities can trace them</li>
      <li><strong>Victims don't report:</strong> You can't go to police and admit you tried to buy cannabis illegally</li>
    </ul>

    <div class="alert alert--danger">
      <strong>Golden Rule:</strong> If someone is offering cannabis delivery via WhatsApp, Telegram, stickers, or online—they are a scammer. Do not send money. Do not engage. Block immediately.
    </div>
  </section>

  <section id="online-scams">
    <h2>Scam #4: Social Media & Online Offers</h2>

    <p><strong>Where it happens:</strong> Instagram DMs, Reddit, Facebook groups, fake "weedmaps" profiles</p>

    <p>Scammers also operate on social media, posing as "cannabis delivery services," "club scouts," or even fake cannabis dispensary accounts.</p>

    <h3>Instagram and DM Scams</h3>

    <p>You search "cannabis Madrid" on Instagram and find profiles with 1000+ followers, professional photos of cannabis, and a bio like "🌱 Madrid's Best Cannabis 🌱 DM for orders."</p>

    <p>You DM them. They respond quickly and professionally. They ask for your address (for delivery, they claim) and payment via Wise or bank transfer. You send money. No delivery. The profile is deleted within days.</p>

    <h3>Fake "Weedmaps" Profiles</h3>

    <p>Scammers create Google Business profiles, Yelp entries, or fake "weedmaps" listings for non-existent cannabis clubs. Reviews are fake (5-star ratings, obviously AI-generated text). The address leads to an empty building or a random residential address. When you try to visit, no one is there. The "club" has vanished.</p>

    <h3>Reddit and Facebook Groups</h3>

    <p>In tourist groups for Madrid ("Digital Nomads Madrid," "Visitors to Spain," etc.), scammers post:</p>

    <p><em>"Hi! I run a cannabis delivery service in Madrid. Very discreet, very safe. I deliver to hostels and hotels. WhatsApp me: +34..."</em></p>

    <p>They look and sound legit. They're not. Same pattern: advance payment, no delivery.</p>

    <h3>How to Verify Before Messaging</h3>

    <ul>
      <li><strong>Check the profile creation date:</strong> Real cannabis clubs have older accounts with consistent activity over years. Scam accounts are brand new or dormant for months, then suddenly active.</li>
      <li><strong>Check the reviews:</strong> Real clubs have reviews from verified members on trusted platforms (Google Maps, Trustpilot). Fake clubs have vague 5-star reviews that sound generic.</li>
      <li><strong>Look for physical address and legal info:</strong> Real clubs display a Spanish address, legal non-profit registration, and tax ID (CIF). Fake ones have no verifiable info.</li>
      <li><strong>Never DM first:</strong> If you message a cannabis account on Instagram and they respond within minutes promising fast delivery—it's a scam.</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section id="how-to-verify">
    <h2>5 Signs You're Dealing with a Real Club</h2>

    <p>Legitimate cannabis social clubs in Madrid operate under strict Spanish law. Here's what distinguishes a real club from a scam:</p>

    <h3>1. They Require a Member Referral (Non-Negotiable)</h3>

    <p>Real clubs do not recruit on the street, via WhatsApp, or on Instagram. You must be invited by an existing member. If someone is recruiting you in person or online, they are not a real club.</p>

    <h3>2. They Have a Fixed, Legal Address</h3>

    <p>A real club operates from a fixed location. You can verify the address exists, matches the club name, and is registered as a non-profit association with Spain's Registry of Associations. If a club keeps changing locations or refuses to give an address—it's fake.</p>

    <h3>3. They Check Your ID and Verify Residency</h3>

    <p>Real clubs are required by Spanish law to:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Verify your age (18+)</li>
      <li>Record your name and ID number</li>
      <li>Confirm you're not a minor or banned member</li>
    </ul>

    <p>They issue a membership card after this process. If a club waves ID checks or takes cash without paperwork, it's a scam.</p>

    <h3>4. They Have Transparent Pricing and a Menu</h3>

    <p>Real clubs post prices per gram or per unit (€8-20, depending on quality and supply). They show what's in stock. They don't haggle or demand cash upfront from strangers. If you ask "how much?" and get a vague response, walk away.</p>

    <h3>5. They're Registered as Non-Profit Associations</h3>

    <p>Real clubs operate as registered non-profit associations. You can verify this by:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Searching the club name on <strong>Registro de Asociaciones de Madrid</strong> (Madrid's official association registry)</li>
      <li>Asking for their CIF (Spanish tax ID) and verifying it on AEAT.es</li>
      <li>Requesting a copy of their estatutos (bylaws), which all real clubs have</li>
    </ul>

    <p>If a club cannot provide this information or claims "they're registered but don't have paperwork," they're operating illegally and are likely a scam.</p>
  </section>

