  <section id="got-scammed">
    <h2>What to Do If You Got Scammed</h2>

    <h3>If You Lost Money to a Delivery Scam (Wise/PayPal/Bank Transfer)</h3>

    <p><strong>Act within 48 hours.</strong></p>

    <ol>
      <li><strong>Contact your bank or payment service immediately:</strong> Tell them the transaction was fraudulent. Wise, PayPal, and most banks allow chargebacks for fraud within 30-120 days. There's a reasonable chance you get your money back.</li>
      <li><strong>Block the contact on all platforms:</strong> WhatsApp, Telegram, email. Don't respond to follow-up messages ("Sorry bro, I'll send tomorrow!").</li>
      <li><strong>Screenshot everything:</strong> Keep all messages, transaction receipts, and profiles as evidence.</li>
      <li><strong>Report the profile/account:</strong> Report the WhatsApp number, Telegram account, or Instagram profile to the platform for fraud. Include evidence.</li>
      <li><strong>Do not report to Spanish police.</strong> Reporting a cannabis scam to police requires admitting you attempted an illegal purchase. Spanish authorities may open a case against you for attempting to buy cannabis, even though you were scammed. The risk outweighs any recovery.</li>
    </ol>

    <h3>If You Got Scammed by a Street Dealer or Fake Club</h3>

    <p><strong>Unfortunately, cash is gone.</strong></p>

    <p>If you paid cash to a street dealer or fake club recruiter, recovery is nearly impossible. Street scammers disappear into crowds; fake club locations are either fake addresses or temporary meetup points. Your money is lost.</p>

    <p><strong>Do not:</strong></p>
    <ul>
      <li>Try to confront the scammer ("Maybe if I find him again...")</li>
      <li>Arrange a "meet to get your money back" (they will rob you or worse)</li>
      <li>Report to police (you'll be admitting to an illegal transaction)</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>If You Got Sick from Synthetic Cannabinoids</h3>

    <p>If you took something from a street dealer and experienced rapid heart rate, chest pain, seizures, or severe anxiety, you need immediate medical help:</p>

    <ul>
      <li><strong>Call 112 (Spain's emergency number)</strong> or go directly to the nearest hospital ER</li>
      <li><strong>Be honest with the doctor:</strong> Tell them you consumed an unknown substance from a street dealer. Doctors in Madrid are trained for this and won't report recreational use. They need to know what symptoms to treat.</li>
      <li><strong>Hospitals that handle synthetic cannabinoid overdoses:</strong> Hospital Clínico San Carlos, Hospital Gregorio Marañón, Hospital 12 de Octubre (all in Madrid)</li>
    </ul>

    <p>Synthetic cannabinoid poisoning is treatable, but only if you get medical help quickly. It's not worth dying or having permanent organ damage to avoid admitting drug use to a doctor.</p>

    <div class="alert alert--warning">
      <strong>The Hard Truth:</strong> If you were scammed, you've lost money or consumed a fake product. The lesson is worth the cost. The safe, legal, and smart way to access cannabis in Madrid is through a verified social club with a member referral. No street deal, no fake club, no WhatsApp service is worth the risk to your money or your health.
    </div>
  </section>

  <h2 style="margin-top: 2em;">Final Thought</h2>

  <p>Madrid has world-class cannabis clubs with excellent products and fair prices. But they operate in the legal gray zone, which means they require referrals, proper membership, and trust. There are no shortcuts. If someone offers you cannabis on the street, promises fast delivery via WhatsApp, or recruits you for an "exclusive club," they are scamming you. It's that simple.</p>

  <p>The cost of learning this lesson (€50-200 lost) is unfortunately common among tourists. The cost of ignoring it could be much higher: a hospital bill from synthetic cannabinoid poisoning, an administrative fine from police, or worse.</p>

  <p>Skip the scams. Use a real club. Stay safe.</p>

